It appears that the implementation of {{tlsDisableOCSPEndpointCheck}} [here|https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-python-driver/commit/47a67183526530bc8e9ac9ffe5325c5dfd3a0b2e], was flawed.

Note that internally this configuration is tracked as {{ssl_check_ocsp_endpoint}} which is the logical inverse of the public option. The rationale behind this was mentioned in the original PR: 

{quote}I created a new internal option name for 2 reasons:
- it keeps things consistent with all transport-security-related options named
ssl*
- it makes it such that the internal option's value is the negation/inverse of
the tlsInsecure value (i.e if tlsInsecure=true, ssl_check_ocsp_endpoint=false).
This helps in reusing the existing code to normalize options and handle security
options --> see uri_parser.py.{quote}

However, it appears that setting {{tlsDisableOCSPEndpointCheck}} does not result in the right behavior. The internal option, instead of being the boolean inverse of specified value, ends up mimicking it instead:

{noformat}
mc = MongoClient(tlsDisableOCSPEndpointCheck=False)
mc._MongoClient__options._options
Out[9]: {'document_class': <class 'dict'>, 'tz_aware': False, 'connect': True, 'ssl_check_ocsp_endpoint': False}
{noformat}

Consequently, a user explicitly setting this option will end up with incorrect behavior. 

Note however, that the behavior of using the {{tlsInsecure}} option (likely a more common usage pattern than explicitly setting each tls*) works as expected:

{noformat}
mc = MongoClient(tlsInsecure=False)
mc._MongoClient__options._options
Out[11]: {'tlsInsecure': False, 'document_class': <class 'dict'>, 'tz_aware': False, 'connect': True, 'ssl_check_ocsp_endpoint': True, 'ssl_match_hostname': True, 'ssl_cert_reqs': True}
{noformat}

